# AutoForge — Cursor Rules
# AutoML web app: FastAPI backend + vanilla HTML/JS frontend
# Stack: Python 3.11, FastAPI, scikit-learn, pandas, joblib

## Project identity
- Project name: AutoForge
- Purpose: End-to-end AutoML platform for non-technical users
- Backend: FastAPI (app/main.py)
- Frontend: Vanilla HTML/CSS/JS served as static files by FastAPI (frontend/)
- ML engine: scikit-learn + pandas + numpy
- Serialization: joblib

## Code style
- Python: follow PEP 8, max line length 100
- Use type hints on every function signature — no bare `def fn(x)`
- Use f-strings, not .format() or %
- Imports order: stdlib → third-party → local, one blank line between groups
- No commented-out dead code in commits
- Short inline comments only on non-obvious logic

## Architecture rules
- All ML logic lives in app/pipeline/ — never inline in route handlers
- Route handlers in app/routers/ — one file per domain (upload, train, export)
- Shared Pydantic models in app/schemas.py
- Never import frontend files from backend — they are static assets only
- Frontend communicates with backend exclusively via HTTP (fetch API)
- No global mutable state — pass data through function arguments or FastAPI dependencies

## FastAPI specifics
- Use async def for all route handlers
- Use UploadFile for file ingestion endpoints
- Return structured JSON responses with consistent shape:
  { "status": "ok"|"error", "data": ..., "message": "..." }
- Use HTTPException with appropriate status codes — never return 200 on errors
- Add CORS middleware for local dev (origins: ["*"] in dev only)

## ML pipeline rules
- Preprocessing must be a scikit-learn Pipeline object — not loose steps
- Imputer: SimpleImputer(strategy="median") for numeric, most_frequent for categorical
- Encoder: OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown="ignore") for categorical
- Scaler: StandardScaler for numeric features
- Resampling: SMOTE from imbalanced-learn, only if class imbalance ratio > 1.5
- Train/test split: 80/20, random_state=42, stratify on target for classification
- Classification algorithms: RandomForestClassifier + LogisticRegression
- Regression algorithms: RandomForestRegressor + LinearRegression
- Clustering algorithms: KMeans + AgglomerativeClustering
- Model selection: pick best by f1_weighted (classification), r2 (regression), silhouette (clustering)
- Serialize full pipeline (preprocessor + model) with joblib.dump()

## Frontend rules
- Single HTML page per view, no framework, no build step
- Use fetch() for all API calls — no axios or jQuery
- Show a loading spinner during any backend call
- Display errors from the API in a visible red banner — never silently fail
- Keep CSS in a single styles.css — no inline styles except dynamic ones via JS
- No external CDN dependencies — everything must work offline except Google Fonts

## File structure
autoforge/
  app/
    main.py              ← FastAPI app, mounts static, includes routers
    schemas.py           ← Pydantic request/response models
    routers/
      upload.py          ← POST /api/upload
      train.py           ← POST /api/train
      export.py          ← GET /api/export/{session_id}
    pipeline/
      preprocessor.py    ← build_preprocessor(df, target, task)
      trainer.py         ← train_and_evaluate(X, y, task)
      evaluator.py       ← compute_metrics(y_true, y_pred, task)
  frontend/
    index.html
    styles.css
    app.js
  models/                ← joblib files saved here, gitignored
  requirements.txt
  .cursorrules
  .gitignore
  README.md

## What NOT to do
- Do not use Flask — project uses FastAPI
- Do not use Streamlit — frontend must be HTML/JS per requirements
- Do not pickle models — use joblib exclusively
- Do not hardcode file paths — use pathlib.Path throughout
- Do not train models synchronously in the request thread for large datasets
  (use BackgroundTasks or just warn the user to wait)
- Do not install torch, tensorflow, or any deep learning library — overkill for this project
- Do not generate placeholder or TODO comments — write working code only

## Environment (Ubuntu 22.04)
- Python 3.11 via system or venv
- Always use a virtualenv: python3 -m venv venv && source venv/bin/activate
- Run dev server: uvicorn app.main:app --reload --port 8000
- Frontend served at: http://localhost:8000
- API docs at: http://localhost:8000/docs
